WEBVTT

00:02.191 --> 00:03.292
Dr. Richardson? You came well, sir. Who are you? 
Okay. My name is Herbert H. Richardson.

00:16.749 --> 00:23.878
Born in Lynn, Massachusetts, in 1930, September 
24, 1930.

00:29.044 --> 00:31.287
Shortly after I was born, family moved to Maine to a 
small town called Bridgeton. Bridgeton.

00:40.336 --> 00:40.816
Bridgeton. About, at that time, 3,000 people. 
Where is Bridgeton? Population. Bridgeton is

00:48.503 --> 00:54.289
approximately 40 miles north of Portland. Okay. 
It's near the Sebago Lake region. We spent a week or

00:57.632 --> 00:59.113
two there. I really enjoyed it. The people were 
nice. It's very pretty up there in Paul.

01:11.847 --> 01:27.970
My father started out as a blacksmith and a 
mechanic, and then

01:11.847 --> 01:27.970
later on when automobiles began to come in and and 
so on, he got into the machine trades. Actually

01:38.604 --> 01:43.891
lived in the small town of Bridgeton early in his 
career. Moved to Massachusetts, where he worked

01:45.753 --> 01:58.750
in the Navy Yard on submarines and other precision 
devices used during the war. and continued in that

02:00.046 --> 02:05.772
kind of work until after I was born, and that was 
during the Depression. There was not a very good

02:07.934 --> 02:23.511
situation down there, so that led him to move with 
the family back to Maine, where he started a small

02:07.934 --> 02:23.511
business doing welding and blacksmith work and 
machine work. Eventually developed that into a

02:25.333 --> 02:29.597
very thriving business designing and building 
snow plows. It was a good market for snow plows.

02:36.232 --> 02:42.079
Motorized on a tractor type device or just the plow 
itself? Mounted on a truck. Developed one of the

02:44.402 --> 02:56.538
first hydraulic systems for positioning the plow 
and the wings that it used to set back snow banks at

02:44.402 --> 02:56.538
the side of the road. Did he patent those? He had 
some patents on hydraulic systems.

03:04.427 --> 03:14.462
So anyways, I grew up, he wanted me to be an engineer 
and wanted me to take over the business. So by the

03:15.925 --> 03:25.099
time I was eight years old, I was working in the 
business operating machine tools. I had to have a

03:26.682 --> 03:29.927
bench to stand on so I could reach the controls. I 
learned welding, machining, all those kinds of

03:31.690 --> 03:37.078
things. I did work in the business part-time all 
the way through high school. During the time that

03:47.434 --> 03:53.263
my father lived in Massachusetts, he worked in a in 
a machine shop called Olmsted and Flint Company,

03:54.391 --> 04:03.981
which is located in Cambridge, adjacent to the MIT 
campus. And he got acquainted with a large number

04:05.803 --> 04:11.809
of MIT students. They used to come over and watch 
him work and shop. And so he developed an

04:18.416 --> 04:22.660
aspiration for me to go to MIT. and become an 
engineer. Well, the high school that I went to had a

04:27.354 --> 04:33.802
total of about 200 students. And no one from that 
school had ever gone out of state to college. And

04:41.051 --> 04:42.974
most did not go to college in state. At any rate, I 
ended up deciding I did not want to be an engineer.

04:52.357 --> 04:54.019
but wanted to go into physics. And so I applied and 
was accepted to Colby College, a very high quality

04:55.240 --> 05:04.349
liberal arts school. Went there against the 
advice of the high school principal, who told me

05:04.409 --> 05:13.858
that I probably wouldn't make it there and should 
go to the University of Maine. So I went to Colby and

05:16.100 --> 05:20.524
had kind of a kind of a hard time because my 
preparation in high school wasn't very good. But I

05:28.336 --> 05:41.130
ended the first semester with a perfect record and 
found out that physics wasn't quite what I wanted

05:28.336 --> 05:41.130
to do and that maybe the old man was right. And so I 
went down to Cambridge and applied to MIT. At the

05:51.436 --> 05:59.969
end of the year, I had a perfect day record at Colby, 
so there was no question about being admitted. And

06:02.133 --> 06:06.519
that's how I started my MIT career.

06:09.364 --> 06:14.231
When year

06:09.364 --> 06:14.231
is that, roughly? It was 1948 was when I started at 
Colby and at 49. And I

06:20.647 --> 06:30.660
really liked it there at the Institute. I did major 
in mechanical engineering. Mechanical

06:33.584 --> 06:36.308
engineering was the next question. What did you 
think you would be doing as a mechanical engineer?

06:40.454 --> 06:42.657
Railroad work at that time? No, designing 
machinery, essentially. But as I went through the

06:47.326 --> 06:51.472
program, my interests changed. And I became, in my 
junior and senior year, very interested in the

06:51.592 --> 07:00.724
emerging area of automatic control. And so I was in 
what they called the Honors Program, which was a

07:02.667 --> 07:17.046
five-year program where you could do one thesis 
and get two degrees. I was offered an opportunity

07:18.663 --> 07:28.617
to work in one of the wartime laboratories, the 
Dynamic Analysis and Control Laboratory. That

07:30.140 --> 07:30.961
was at MIT. At MIT. It was, at the time, doing work on 
guided missiles. And I joined a group that was

07:37.911 --> 07:48.366
developing the electro-hydraulic controls for 
the Meteor missile, which was the first.

07:49.578 --> 07:56.047
autonomous

07:49.578 --> 07:56.047
guided missile. There's another one thing that I 
just finished doing. I was writing a history of

