34:05.113 --> 34:06.195
Beginning... really with Perry Atkinson's 
administration, that there began to be some

34:07.036 --> 34:28.447
long-range thinking about what the A&M system 
should be and what its mission should be in the

34:07.036 --> 34:28.447
state and what areas should it try to emphasize and 
de-emphasize.

34:31.051 --> 34:33.955
And I think Perry Atkinson had some very good 
long-range visions as to what the system might

34:35.352 --> 34:44.203
become in the future. I think felt very strongly 
that the emphasis should really be in engineering

34:44.263 --> 34:59.622
and agriculture because that's the place where 
the system has a good deal of strength. Of course,

35:00.864 --> 35:03.587
those universities that came into the system

35:06.318 --> 35:14.228
at that time did not add a lot to those strengths, 
even though there was some agriculture programs.

35:14.268 --> 35:18.254
A&I has a respectable engineering program. You 
wouldn't say that it had much effect on the overall

35:18.354 --> 35:24.422
activity. So there was a lot of soul-searching, I 
think, out of the board during the time Perry was

35:25.944 --> 35:36.257
chancellor. A study was done, I guess about four 
years ago, was the year before Perry announced he

35:38.515 --> 36:07.898
was going to step down, by McKenzie and Company, 
where they looked at

35:38.515 --> 36:07.898
some indicators for higher education throughout 
Texas and compared compared those indicators

36:08.418 --> 36:24.395
with what was going on nationally and looked at 
various attributes of particularly the

36:08.418 --> 36:24.395
universities that were in the system at that time, 
eight of them, and tried to characterize them.

36:25.456 --> 36:33.345
